{"active_answer": "quick slip knot", "active_index": 351, "active_question": "What specific knot is mentioned as a good way to mark the middle of the rope for later reuse?", "audit_index": 1, "decision": "keep", "document_sha256": "b0b19a7d953de1efe052774f459ef7d121086b3c9fba90dc1381b7c56641161d", "fact_id": "fact-ba692623a8506581339b", "prior_review": {"decision": "keep", "path": "data/manual_reviews/context_merit_audit_v16/context_merit_audit_v16.jsonl", "sha256": "5b6c71868c8fed049f239c6aaba780ae6750fa1daac3dd4b5b7e61f97bc86b89", "version": 16}, "reason": "The answer is a non-body rope-handling use, and the surrounding source explicitly warns that slip knots are unstable.", "reason_code": "rope_handling_utility_context_complete", "review_pass": "secondary_prior_keep_reaudit", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v29", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 3, "bare_answer_points": 2, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 19, "risk_score": 2, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v29", "source": "rope365", "source_document": "data/raw/rope365_25f1b23eb40be00e.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "b07e3a74c93de379408d9212fbb5c62c23e214a0f73b8c367c9b691dc4b3ad97", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "| Day 218: Slip Knots – Slip knots are fast, they tighten and they have multiple fun uses if we take into the fact that they are not stable. The basic slip knot can be used for quick capture, and a noose can create an adjustable loop. Because it’s quite fast to tie, a quick slip knot is a good way to mark the middle of the rope in case you want to use your rope again later. | ", "support_evidence_sha256": "33b48319dcf6bd569974ac7248024f0bc385d00e91c7492b853b7ba3ba0b6ee2", "url": "https://rope365.com/more-knots/"}
{"active_answer": "The two-point threshold", "active_index": 257, "active_question": "What is the term for how far apart two points of touching must be to be perceived apart from one unit?", "audit_index": 2, "decision": "edit", "document_sha256": "40b89c879f5a49bc58893c68772a76722fcd9bf09ec9fd2989d83e411f7b8838", "edited_answer": "Communication is key and consent is particularly important with this kind of play.", "edited_question": "What does Rope365 emphasize about communication and consent in pressure-point play?", "fact_id": "fact-bf91b4f8c612c46d312c", "prior_review": {"decision": "keep", "path": "data/manual_reviews/context_merit_audit_v16/context_merit_audit_v16.jsonl", "sha256": "5b6c71868c8fed049f239c6aaba780ae6750fa1daac3dd4b5b7e61f97bc86b89", "version": 16}, "reason": "The edit replaces an awkward tactile-acuity term lookup with the source's more useful communication and consent guidance.", "reason_code": "replace_touch_term_with_individual_consent_context", "review_pass": "secondary_prior_keep_reaudit", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v29", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 3, "bare_answer_points": 2, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 21, "risk_score": 2, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v29", "source": "rope365", "source_document": "data/raw/rope365_02b5a435a4822809.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "a8d6161090bbd7062b45b86bf5b1f161fe53c17f4b9aa3d46e6ae944409ee18b", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "Every person is different, a spot that tickles for someone might do nothing for another, and be extremely painful for someone else. Some may even have pressure points that no one else has. It is best to try the different spots you aim to use before combining them with rope to measure the individual specificities and limit awkward surprise. Communication is key and consent is particularly important with this kind of play.", "support_evidence_sha256": "fbfc7e80e1d807885eabfe3d42ce5370a0f679f1e025795c3b061da8cb4d39d5", "url": "https://rope365.com/touch/"}
{"active_answer": "torii shibari 鳥居縛り", "active_index": 266, "active_question": "What is the traditional Japanese name for the Open Knees tie, which is described as a traditional Japanese gate at a Shinto temple?", "audit_index": 3, "decision": "drop", "document_sha256": "9b251abe61d666b8628d69d2d14dbccb2a7a8286214988b351e462b8f1571112", "fact_id": "fact-7c22eef0a56b8897d476", "prior_review": {"decision": "keep", "path": "data/manual_reviews/context_merit_audit_v16/context_merit_audit_v16.jsonl", "sha256": "5b6c71868c8fed049f239c6aaba780ae6750fa1daac3dd4b5b7e61f97bc86b89", "version": 16}, "reason": "The translated open-knees pose alias adds no safety context, and a more useful discussion-first vulnerability lesson from the same source already survives the projection.", "reason_code": "duplicate_high_risk_pose_alias", "review_pass": "secondary_prior_keep_reaudit", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v29", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 3, "bare_answer_points": 2, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 23, "risk_score": 2, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v29", "source": "rope365", "source_document": "data/raw/rope365_1a9f4f2fef392a9c.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "492453b778b0634eac48d63c8bc4e1efc47f7c571cff513d7dc418bbde80c8f3", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "| Day 156: Open Knees – Alt M-shape, torii shibari 鳥居縛り (traditional Japanese gate at Shinto temple). Create a tie that will keep the knees open. A great way to do that is by tying knees together with the rope going in the back in between. You can also use a chest harness and attach it to each side. The variation with a the knee connected via the back in a straight line is often refered to as moon tie. Inspirations and Resources | ", "support_evidence_sha256": "05d9d1eb1246e329db3511496a0061e09772beae1f4b7877beee8f1b59739cad", "url": "https://rope365.com/exposed/"}
